segments.text: This is an interview with Dr. Lawrence Franks by Scott Chancellor on April 18, 1993, at Nacogdoches, Texas, concerning protest movements and activism by students on the campus of the University of Texas from the mid-1960s to the early 1970s.
In the interest of accumulating knowledge, I'm asking you to donate this tape to me or to the Texas A&M Oral History Collection in the University Archives.
Is that all right with you?
Yes.
Okay, Dr. Franks.
What year and where were you born?
I was born March 28, 1916, Stockman, Texas, in Shelby County.
Okay, what is your educational background?
I finished high school, five years of college with a master's degree and a doctorate from Indiana University in 1955.
Okay, what was your position at the University of Texas?
I went to work at the University of Texas in Austin August 1, 1966 as dean of men.
The areas over which our staff had responsibility were student conduct, student housing, and student organizations.
What years were you there?
I was there from 64 to 77.
Can you describe for me the mood and the atmosphere on campus during these years where you were there?
Yes.
The mood and general climate on college and university campuses all over the country, and particularly on the East Coast and the West Coast, was that of rising wave of activism and protest.
There was a wide range of topics that were being addressed
there and therefore became topics of discussion on the university campus, the University of Texas campus.

And that was over the nation's participation in the various wars, the lack of an aggressive program to promote an increased minority enrollment, university regulations dealing with student conduct on and off campus, women's rights.
and a stronger voice for all students in formulating the new rules and regulations affecting the lives of all the students.
The university campus and the area adjacent to it, the campus became a gathering place for students and non-students to protest these various issues.
The name given to the organization that was formed
was Students for a Democratic Society, an activist group formed on the Michigan campus by Tom Hayden, a meeting place for the new organization that was found across the street from the campus.
One of the early causes represented by the SDS organization was to stage nightly
demonstrations at a lounge across the street from the campus at which a black student had not been allowed to purchase a beer.
Let me add to what I've just said about the demonstration at the lounge.
our role there.
When my staff was represented at one of these demonstrations, and we saw many, we were there as observers.
We were not there to arrest anybody or stop anything that was happening, but to observe and be able to report back to the administration of the university what we perceived happened
on that occasion, or the demonstration were on campus or off campus.
Okay.
What percentage of students would you say were involved with the protest movements?
Oh, that would be too difficult to come close, I expect.
We would have fifty people, a hundred people, and then in the days when we had the largest
of protesters.
One time 20,000 people came to the campus protesting in the Cambodian War and the incident at Kent State where some students were killed by the National Guard.
And of course, on demonstrations such as this, we had faculty members, staff members, citizens of the community, but the hard core
And when I say hardcore, the people who composed the Students for a Democratic Society, that was a very small, very small, but vocal group.
If I were to take a figure, I would say it would be less than 5%.
We had 24,500 students on the campus that first year I was there.
And so it was a small group.
small but vocal.
What type of students were they?
Could you describe how they dressed and describe them?
Well, as we got to know many of them, many of them were brilliant students from other colleges or from UT.
They were not dummies.
They were smart, brilliant people that had some deep-seated causes that they wanted to represent.
Others, however, were sort of an unkempt group that dressed their demeanor, their clothing, their beard, their hair.
And of course, hair became a symbol of the protest movement, long hair.
I talked to many students on the campus
and off the campus about, why did you let your hair grow wrong?
That's just the style.
And I would say, well, does it have anything to do with the protesting, the status quo?
Yes.
Yes.
I think they could be identified as a group whose dress was not like that of the fraternity men or women.
It appeared to me that they
did this on purpose.
The women wore their high-top shoes a lot.
It just didn't look like a little girl was getting ready to go to a party.
A dress was an important part of the protest, I think.
Do you think their dress presented a negative image to

Well, I think for many people, I think there's a stereotypical notion that the dress makes the person, and you can judge a person's character and maybe a lot of other things about him, about the way he dresses.
The banker goes to work with his pinstripe suit on and necktie, you know.
And the farmer goes to the field with his overalls and jumper on.
So I think that there's some mighty fine people that never had a suit of clothes on.
And so we can't conclude that the dress did any more than represent, and I think it did represent a mood.
The mood was, we'll show you that we can dress like this.
I had trouble one time getting a person, whether it was an SDS representative,
They were before a committee on the university campus, and the chairman asked this man to put his cap on, and he refused.
But the chairman told him that he would not proceed with the meeting until he put his cap on.
Well, that was sort of the mood that some of the SDS people presented.
And of course, the university would be just as insistent as we expected to put the camp up in Germany.
And it did.
Okay.
Okay, if you would, discuss SDS on campus, their role with the students, and how the administration dealt with them.
Well, the two or three things about the SDS, Students for a Democratic Society, we got to know some of the individuals personally.
And by the way, there was President's student body, Jeff Jones.
He was a candidate promoted by the SDS, supported by the SDS.
And enough students on the campus
Of course, we weren't having a whole lot of students vote in the election.
And one of their protests of not voting in the election was they didn't have anybody they wanted to vote for.
But one of the members of the SES was the daughter of one of the university professors.
A very fine family, and she's a very fine person.
for she just held that the university's position on some of the issues ought to be addressed and something done about it.
They would stage sit-ins in the building sometime.
They would have a demonstration.
If a recruiter came to the campus, they'd have protests.
If the recruiter were representing something that
some of the areas that contributed to the war effort, they would have a protest.
And the university, I think pretty soon, got to the point that as long as they don't block any passageways, as long as they don't disrupt an activity, as long as they're orderly, let them sit there.
And occasionally you'd find one individual that would
be causing a little bit of trouble and we'd just have to get them out of the building.
And that was handled by the University Police and handled very cautiously and very considerately.
I did not see on the University campus during the years that I was there and during the height of the activism and demonstrations, I didn't see what I would consider active violence.
I saw
had some of the tear gas get in my eyes when I'd be on the campus and sit in at the Student Union one time.
They couldn't get the protesters to come out, so they used the tear gas or mace and got them out of there.
But this was, I guess, as much violence as I witnessed there.
the tires on a couple of university cars were slashed and they were flat when they came out to take them away.
But the university, I think, saw that some of its rules and regulations needed examination.
There's one in particular that marijuana, by the way,
drugs became an issue, and it was believed that one of the places where a lot of the use of marijuana and other drugs was pretty rampant was among the representatives of the SDS group.
Now that's not to say that there weren't others doing it as well, but they

had some people that got into trouble with drugs, and the regents established a very strict rule that says a student who is found in possession of, making any use of, marijuana or any other drug would be expelled from the university.
And so for a few months and maybe a year or two,
the students who were involved on campus or off campus with marijuana or other drugs, hallucinatory drugs, would be expelled from the university.
And I just automatically, in our office, administered that preservation of the regulation.
But we went to court.
And the university lost that case.

That was too strong and too rigid and didn't take room for the first offender, and it didn't take room for a person who just maybe was caught up in an atmosphere where it could be said that they just was led into it.
coerced into it.
So that rule was changed.
Another issue that, of course, had been mentioned was the minority enrollment.
The university hired a Mrs. Duren, a black woman, a very fine white woman, to represent the black students' causes on the campus.
She was known as an advocate or an ombudsman, but her sole responsibility was to listen to, counsel, encourage, do whatever she could to promote the black students' interests and concerns.
And she did a fine job.
And I think, generally speaking, the people on the university campus were interested in
promoting enrollment of the blacks, encouraging them to come.
And I, during the thirteen years I was there, I was involved with the orientation programs for the new students, and I would make it a point to meet all the students, and I specifically
would go to the black students, the Spanish students, any students that were not Anglo, and I would try to make them feel welcome.
But I noticed in the last few years, and I always had to make the overture, but I noticed the last two or three years that I was there, the black students were making overtures toward me.
They'd see me stand over there and find out I was associated with the university, and they'd come over there and they'd say, what's your job, what do you do, what, so on and so forth.
So I found a more relaxed atmosphere.
That's not to say that they've ever until now achieved the kind of enrollment for the blacks that they need to have or want to have.
But there was a great change while I was there.
And of course, as you say that, you may be telling about the change that one goes through himself.
I had the experience of working with 125 black people in the Navy.
And I found out that while I was working to try to get to know them, I was learning a lot about myself.
And so I think that would be true
of the experience there.
Alright, are there any specific problems or violations with SES that you remember?
Yes, the one that comes to my mind first is that Vice President, presidential candidate Hubert Humphreys was to speak in the city auditorium in Austin on Sunday.
And on Saturday, the SDS organization held a rally up on the mall, the West Mall of the campus, getting organized for a protest at the Hubert Umpress speaking downtown.
And they were charged by the university through the student organization's office.
they were charged for having an unauthorized rally, and they were taken before a committee.
And of course, the position of the SDS and those who argued and they were hacked was that that was prohibiting Iraq to assemble.
But the university had some stated rules and regulations

demonstrations on the campus about use of university facilities, and they had to drop off a piece of paper that would indicate that they were going to have this happening, this event on the campus, and they didn't do that.
And so there was a great deal of problem of getting a committee.
We had a list of thirty faculty members from
which we could pick three faculty members and two students from the student list that formed the committee to hear the case.
And with the help of some of the activist professors, the students representing the SDS, they eliminated 27 of the faculty members, to call a name.
that's in the legal terms, they call it pre-entry.
That's not the word.
Pre-entry, I guess it may be.
Pre-empt to challenge.
And it means you could challenge without cause and get rid of this fellow, that fellow.
But the final one to the hearing, and it was a lengthy one, and I think I mentioned on the tape about the man who wouldn't put his cap on.
But then the records that you found suggest that they were kicked off of the campus for some regulation violation and were off from April to November or something like that.
I don't remember the specifics of that, but it may well be that as a result of
their unauthorized assembly.
Failure to have permission, they were put off and then allowed to come back in November.
As a result of this experience, the university set up a free speech area.
There's an area
on the campus, and it happened to be the West Mall where the demonstration had been held when they were to go down to the auditorium and protest on Prince Pete's.
That area was designated, and still the students or student organizations were to come by and reserve that time so there wouldn't be two or three groups at the same time.
So the procedure was
You could use it any time you wanted to, for whatever purpose you wanted to, student organization.
But they had, they had known in the Student Activities Office.
Sorry to disdain you.
Could you discuss the university rules and regulations, and do you feel they restricted individual rights for the students?
Well, let's talk about regulations generally.
I think it's incumbent upon a college or university to have some stated goals, some academic goals, and have some rules and regulations concerning academic matters.
And I think it's appropriate to have some rules and regulations concerning the students' conduct and behavior.
Now, of course, one of the most debated issues in recent years has been the hair and dress.
And students' schools are still, some of them today,
saying your hair cannot be any longer than touching the collar and so on.
But they found that they just can't win those in court over and over again in trying to say how long your hair's got to be or how you have to dress.
But I think you have to have some rules, some expectations that the university states in its general catalog is why it's usually found.
expectations of the student, and I think the protest movements have, in general, moved the universities and colleges into a more open field and more open atmosphere.
And, of course, with life, where you gain something, you give up something.
And I think that some of the rules that were considered restrictive by some students, they're actually rules that the purpose by which they were formulated are still genuine and good.
But when a student wants to do their own thing or a person wants to do his own thing,
They have to realize that each area, each of our lives, and each environment in which we find ourselves has some expectations.
And it could well be said, I think, that traditionally the teachers took the place of the parents
The colleges and universities said, bring your son or daughter, sons and daughters to us and we'll look after them.
And so the parents had come to expect that, some of them, and so there has to be rules.
There needs to be as much freedom of choice as can be given within the framework
of the mission of a college or university.
Now, I happen to hold the notion that it's all right to teach right and wrong.
It's all right to say it's wrong to lie.
It's wrong to steal.
It's wrong to cheat.
And some people say, well, that's none of your business.
But if someone is cheating in the classroom, there has to be rules and regulations to govern that.
There's someone's behavior.
as interfering with the rights of others, there has to be some rule and regulation and procedure and machinery to deal with it.
So I think that the intent of a rule should be to give the individual student the right to grow and develop as much as they can on their own, but there are certain limits.
It's like the road sign.
It's like the road map.
When you get ready to travel, you take a road map and you plot out your course.
And you learn where the rough places are in the road.
And if there's a detour, you move around the detour.
But I think that rules are not ugly words.
Rules are not bad things.
Now, the rules can be over-restricted, but I think freedom itself carries a lot of responsibility, and the university, colleges and universities have to have them.
They have to update them, but the freedom to do one's own thing all the time is just not something
that's available to all of us.
There's an environment on the college or university campus that has to be structured in a rather orderly fashion, and that's what I would think about the rules and regulations.
Do you think the rules and regulations the university had were appropriate for the times?
No, no, because we didn't have any rules and regulations concerning use of space or free speech areas.
We had to designate, needed to designate a place where students could assemble any time they wanted to.
And I'm remembering, believing that
They just made it known to the Activities Office that they would be holding a demonstration at 10 o'clock on West Mall on Wednesday.
And so that if a crowd got up there, they'd be authorized, that is to say.
That space had been reserved for them.
So, yeah, they were pretty restrictive.
And there were a lot of
the can's and cannot's and do's and do not's that I think were, some of them were restricted.
But the expectation on the part of an individual or a group to say, well I'll be able to go out and demonstrate anytime I want to on the campus.
And many times there's an event going on
on the campus, a lot of people on the campus, and it would interfere.
It would interfere with that.

Of course, I'm sure some colleges and universities would be tempted, and some of them may have, to select some free speech area that's pretty well out of sight, and that's not what the demonstrators want.
They want to be out front where they can be seen.
I guess I've already said it.
Some of the restrictions were restricted and didn't maybe provide the kind of freedom that students should have, just like living in the dormitory.
We used to require there that freshmen and sophomores had to live in the University of
The housing where we used to supervise off-campus housing, the regents took us out of that.
They said the students could live wherever they wanted to.
When I first went to the university, a student lived at Ms. Adams' boarding house and hadn't paid the board bill, but she'd report it to us and we'd say,
pay your board bill or you'll be dropped out of school.
In order to stay in school, pay your board bill.
And I could even, at the old store downtown, they could be barred from readmission until that bill was paid.
Well, that was too much involvement in a person's private life.
